      "id": "wq-NAT-1774714183001",
      "itemVersion": 4,
      "created": "2026-03-28T16:09:43.241Z",
      "source": "natasha",
      "assignee": "natasha",
      "priority": "idea",
      "status": "incubating",
      "title": "Natasha: benchmark rcc/dashboard Rust/WASM build time with sccache vs Boris L40 cross-compile",
      "description": "Sparky's sccache setup (a8ea0d4) achieves cold ~26s, warm ~9s builds on aarch64. Boris has 4x L40 GPUs and x86_64 \u2014 hypothetically cross-compilation from Boris to WASM could leverage his CPU cores for faster build. Explore: (1) set up cross-compile from boris-sweden targeting wasm32-unknown-unknown, (2) compare wall-clock build time vs sparky native, (3) determine if distributed compile (sccache shared cache via MinIO) would benefit the whole team. Low priority \u2014 informational for developer workflow.",
      "notes": "",
      "preferred_executor": "gpu",
      "journal": [
        {
          "ts": "2026-03-28T16:38:12.866Z",
          "author": "natasha",
          "type": "claim",
          "text": "Claimed"
        },
        {
          "ts": "2026-03-28T16:38:12.997Z",
          "author": "natasha",
          "type": "comment",
          "text": "Natasha review: sccache on aarch64 is already effective (9s warm build). Cross-compile from Boris adds complexity with uncertain gains since WASM builds are CPU-bound, not GPU-bound. The distributed sccache-via-MinIO angle is the most practical thread \u2014 would benefit all agents. Low priority but worth tracking for when build times become a friction point. Suggest incubating."
        },
        {
          "ts": "2026-03-28T16:38:35.053Z",
          "author": "api",
          "type": "status-change",
          "text": "Updated: status: \"in-progress\" \u2192 \"incubating\""
